label.value: abnormal spleen B cell corona morphology

value.value: any structural anomaly of the area of the spleen secondary B follicle that surrounds the germinal center and harbors the small recirculating B lymphocytes
any structural anomaly of the blood vessel surrounded by the periarteriolar lymphoid sheath that connects the trabecular artery to the trabecular vein

any structural anomaly of the zone between the red and white pulp of the spleen containing numerous macrophages and lymphocytes, and a rich plexus of sinusoids supplied by white pulp arterioles carrying blood-borne antigens

definition.value: Note that there is no consensus in the literature about which compartments constitute the white pulp or the ramifications of the microvasculature. In addition, notable differences exist between humans and rodents. In this ontology, the marginal zone has been included as part of the white pulp.

value.value: any structural anomaly of the border region surrounding the spleen B cell follicles and the periarteriolar lymphoid sheath (PALS) that separates it from the marginal zone that mediates lymphocyte entry into the white pulp from the blood

definition.value: Note that there is no consensus in the literature about which compartments constitute the white pulp or the ramifications of the microvasculature. In addition, notable differences exist between humans and rodents. In this ontology, the marginal sinus (which may not exist in human) has been included as part of the white pulp. The perifollicular zone, which is present in human and not rodents, may be the functional equivalent of the marginal sinus in rodents.

value.value: deviation from the normal size of the thymus
any structural anomaly of the basic structural unit of the thymus
any structural anomaly of the fibrous connective tissue surrounding the thymus
any structural anomaly of the epithelial cells lining the capsule and trabeculae of the thymus
any structural anomaly of the thymic connective tissue which extends into the parenchyma
any structural anomaly of the outer part of a thymus lobule that surrounds the medulla and is composed of closely packed lymphocytes

definition.value: The thymic cortex contains immature thymocytes, cortical epithelial cells, and scattered macrophages.

value.value: any structural anomaly of the inner area of thymus lobules

definition.value: The thymic medulla contains mature thymocytes, medulla epithelial cells, macrophages and dendritic cells.

value.value: any functional anomaly of the immunocompetent cells of the lymphoid and hemopoietic systems and skin, which function to process antigens and present them to T cells, thus stimulating cellular immunity
any structural anomaly of the regional immune system associated with the mucosa
any structural anomaly of the regional immune system located in the gut
any structural anomaly of the circular lymphoid tissue formed by the lingual, pharyngeal, and facial tonsils
any structural anomaly of either of the two small almond-shaped masses of lymph tissue found on either side of the oropharynx
any structural anomaly of the lymph tissue in the roof and posterior wall of the nasopharynx
any structural anomaly of the lymph tissue on the floor of the oropharyngeal passage, near the root of the tongue
any structural anomaly of the lymph tissue associated with the pharyngeal opening of the auditory tube
any structural anomaly of the specialized epithelium of the Peyer's patch

definition.value: Antigen normally enters the Peyer's patch via this specialized epithelium.

value.value: any structural anomaly of the area of the Peyer's patch normally occupied by B cells

label.value: abnormal Peyer's patch germinal center morphology

value.value: any structural anomaly of the area of the Peyer's patch where B cells proliferate and differentiate into plasma cells

definition.value: Germinal centers are often identified by the binding of peanut agglutinin (PNA).

label.value: abnormal Peyer's patch T cell area morphology

value.value: any structural anomaly of the Peyer's patch area normally occupied by T lymphocytes
any structural anomaly of the regional immune system located near the bronchus
any structural or developmental anomaly of the blood cells or the organs associated with the development and formation of blood cells
any structural anomaly of the soft tissue that fills the cavities of bones

definition.value: Note that this term refers to the contents of the bone marrow cavity, not to the structure of the cavity itself.

value.value: any structural anomaly of the cells found in the bone marrow
any structural anomaly of the cells that give rise to most types of cells necessary for fetal development
any structural anomaly of the specialized cells that are committed to giving rise to cells with particular functions

atypical formation of lymphocytes and plasma cells from lymphoid stem cells which develop from the pluripotent hematopoietic stem cells in the bone marrow; lymphoid stem cells differentiate into T-lymphocytes; B-lymphocytes; plasma cells; or NK-cells (natural killer cells), depending on the organ or tissues to which they migrate

any structural anomaly of the cells in the B lymphocyte lineage that have undergone VDJ rearrangement of the immunoglobulin heavy chain and are in the process of V-J rearrangement of the light chain: these cells express mu heavy chain on the cell surface

definition.value: These cells express the mu heavy chain in both the cytoplasm and on the cell surface; in addition to the mu heavy chain, other cell surface markers include CD45R, MHC class II, CD19, CD20, CD38, and CD40.

value.value: greater than the expected number of a benign epithelial neoplasm with a glandular organization arising in the small and/or large intestine, occurring in a specific population in a given time period
local accumulation of fluid, plasma proteins, and leukocytes in the respiratory system
greater likelihood that an organism will develop ill effects from a pathogenic invasion or from components of or toxins produced by pathogens
any structural anomaly of the subset of T cells found in the thymus that express neither CD4 nor CD8

definition.value: These are precursors to mature T cells; normally, they do not circulate, but are found in the thymus and they have not undergone rearrangement of the alpha and beta T cell receptor genes.

value.value: any anomaly of the subset of T cells found in the thymus that express both CD4 and CD8

definition.value: These cells are precursors to mature T cells and are generally located in the thymus; during their development, the alpha and beta chains of the T cell receptor are rearranged and the TCR receptor can be expressed.

value.value: reduced likelihood that an organism will develop ill effects from a pathogenic invasion or from components of or toxins produced by pathogens
reduced likelihood that an organism will develop ill effects from a viral infection or from components of or toxins produced by a virus
reduced likelihood that an organism will develop ill effects from a bacterial infection or from components of or toxins produced by bacteria
greater likelihood that an organism will develop ill effects from a bacterial infection or from components of or toxins produced by bacteria
any structural anomaly of the progenitor cells of the thrombocytic (platelet) line of cells
any structural anomaly of the cells found in the bone marrow that give rise to the granulocyte line of blood cells
atypical production of or inability to produce the granular leukocytes that have a three- to five-lobed nucleus and a cytoplasm that contains inconspicuous granules stainable by neutral dyes
any structural anomaly of the immature, nucleated erythrocyte precursors that give rise to reticulocytes and are derived from erythroid progenitor cells
any structural anomaly of a giant cell 50 to 100 micron in diameter, with a greatly lobulated nucleus, found in the bone marrow; mature blood platelets are released from its cytoplasm
greater likelihood that an organism will develop ill effects from a viral infection or from components of or toxins produced by a virus

anomaly in the function of the early phase of the response to infection; normally, it is present at all times, does not increase with exposure to specific pathogens, and does not discriminate between pathogens
anomaly in the function of the response of antigen-specific lymphocytes to antigen, including the development of immunological memory
abnormal function of any adaptive immune response in which T cells play a main role

any structural anomaly of the immature or mature forms of a granular leukocyte that in its mature form has an irregularly shaped, pale-staining nucleus that is partially constricted into two lobes, and with cytoplasm that contains coarse, bluish-black granules of variable size; these cells contain vasoactive amines such as histamine and serotonin, which are released on appropriate stimulation
